19:28:47","updated":"2021-11-06 20:52:06","type":"status","message":"Hi all, Sharing my experience for vande bharat travel from Mumbai to Newark to Seattle. (26th June) I am on h4 visa and i travlled with my husband who is on h1b. We booked the flights with a grt difficulty on 6th june for 26th june. Our flight was at 1.30 am and as per few people's experience, we reached airport at 7.30 pm. There was already a queue with people coming from all over india like gujarat etc. When asked to the security, they told that the AI staff will come by 9.30. Once the AI staff came they started distributing the health declaration and 1 deportation form per person. Then at around 10 they started taking wheel chair assisted people and then the common people but they started taking the 2nd queue first bcz of which a huge argument occurred between the people of 1st queue and AI staff. Finally at 11 they started taking people 1 by 1 and temp check was done, passport check and finally were allowed to enter airport at 11.30. Inside again we had to submit the health form and stamp was done on one of the forms. After that we were sent to check-in line for baggage drop. There too AI staff wasn't clear on new visa restrictions and she took more than 25 mins to get it clarified and finally checked in our baggage at 12.25 am. Not to forget,our name was selected for extra baggage scanning( random pickup) which took extra 10 mins of time before we could check in our baggage. Post this we stood in the immigration line and we were done with it by 1.10 am. By the time immigration was done, it was already time for boarding. So since the time we arrived at airpoat, we didnt get a chance to sit till 1.30 am. Before reaching the boarding gates, we were given mask, shield and few sachet of sanitizer. Middle seat people were given a ppe kit which was comfortable enough to carry throughout the journey. Inside the plane, there were food packets kept at each seat with sufficient food for 16 hr journey. There were 2 food packets in each plastic bag with frooti, sandwich, roll, kachori, peanuts, aloo bhujiya, cake, muffin, chips , banana, apple and few other small items. Also each seat has 2 bottles of 0.5lt water and 1 more 0.5 lt bottle inside food packet. No other in plane service was provided. Could see a lot of young mothers with babies ranging from 6 months to 6 years travelling. I would suggest to take namaskar service if you travelling with child and lots of luggage . They were providing bassinets i think if you have booked them in advance. Cannot say about airplane washrooms bcz i didnt use the restroom. Airport restrooms were quite clean. Our flight started 30 min late. The journey itself was smooth but no social distancing was followed inside plane or outside airport in the queue. We reached newark on time and deplaned and went straight to the immigration which was pretty smooth and was over in 30 mins after disembarking. Collected the luggage and headed towards the domestic transfer since we had an American airlines from newark to Seattle via Charlotte at 1.30pm newark time. We had to pay extra for luggage since the flight only provided carry on baggae service. We reached Seattle before time and took a Lyft to home. We have self quarantined ourself for 14 days at home for everyones safety. Happy to be curtailed a lot of my activities, but it has also taught me to try and make the best of every situation and enjoy life’s little moments. Writing poetry, dancing and cooking are my three passions. I started writing poetry when I was in college but was only able to devote more time to it after I retired from my job as a teacher. My poems were being published in Rashtra Darpan magazine, but the publishing has stalled during the lockdown. So, I live-stream my poems every Saturday and have been getting a good response. My husband and I moved to Decatur, Georgia from Rockford, Illinois after retirement to be our only son and his family. I am a people person and I love cooking. I made many friends after moving here and had formed two small social groups, Sakhi and the Lovely Golden Girls. I would host a lot of get-togethers and chaat parties at home or in the park, where we would meet, chat, laugh and have a good time in general. I have not been able to do that for the past few months due to social distancing. We try to meet up on Zoom and Facebook, but I still miss the face to face interaction. I started dancing when I was four years old and later received formal training in Bharatanatyam and Manipuri styles. I am 77 now, but I still love to dance. I had also formed a seniors Garba group. We taught and coordinated performances at temples during festivals and for other special occasions. I miss my dance performances the most of all, but I continue to dance at home for my own pleasure. I tell Echo to play Bollywood music and just start dancing when nobody is around. That is why when I saw the NRI Pulse Life in Lockdown series, I wanted to make and share a dance video about my life in lockdown.\" Submit your 'Life in Lockdown' story at editor@nripulse.com. - PPE. This project was originally started with 2 people and today, we feel proud of all volunteers who helped us in this initiative to reach this goal. They are sewing masks daily to help us donate at various health centers, shelter homes, low income families, homeless folks and lot many people. We had limited funds to start and there was indeed a big cost involved to buy fabric, elastic and other PPEs. We faced so many challenges to get elastic and calling Joan and Ben n Franklin was our daily routine to grab elastic as soon as they get in stock. Very thankful to donors who gave us funds and really nice of some of them who donated fabric and elastic too. We donated masks in New York, California, Oregon and even in India while helping women in need and paying them to create jobs for them. Project Mask added other donations like food and groceries, personal hygiene items etc. too and today we have helped over 25,000 people and still not done! Leaders behind screen program has helped over 300 kids (per class per kid) with free online classes offered by our youth board. While we take a proud moment to announce these numbers, we know that this is just the beginning! We will continue helping others in need and making masks.
